# Project Coding Standards and Guidelines

1. Our backend is developed in Python.
2. Our frontend is built using React.
3. All code must follow software engineering best practices.
4. Avoid any redundancy in function logic or naming across modules.
5. Never include inline comments in code. Use descriptive function and variable names instead.
6. Follow PEP-8 for Python code styling.
7. All Python functions must include Google-style docstrings.
8. Use modular, reusable, and testable code structures.
9. Prioritize maintainability, performance, and scalability in every component.
10. Use black and isort for automatic code formatting and import sorting.
11. All Python code must be tested using pytest.
12. All business logic should be separated from controllers and view layers.
13. Never modify files in the `/core/utils` directory unless explicitly approved by maintainers.
14. Do not use deprecated or unstable APIs.
15. React code must be structured using functional components and hooks only.
16. Use TypeScript for all React components.
17. Use TailwindCSS for UI styling in React.
18. All components must be fully accessible (WCAG 2.1 compliant).
19. Avoid any global state unless using a defined state management strategy (e.g., Zustand or Redux Toolkit).
20. All new features must include appropriate unit and integration tests.
21. Always validate prompt inputs and model outputs against business rules.
22. No code should go to production without peer review and approval.
23. The system is deployed on Hostinger and must remain fully operational at all times.
24. Never modify code directly on the server to ensure the deployed version mirrors the local repository.
25. You are allowed to run commands directly in the terminal for deployment and maintenance purposes.
